"Betty" was written and storyboarded by Ako Castuera and [[Jesse_Moynihan|Jesse Moynihan]], from a story by [[Kent_Osborne|Kent Osborne]], [[Pendleton_Ward|Pendleton Ward]], Jack Pendarvis, Adam Muto, and Moynihan. Art direction was handled by Nick Jennings, whereas supervising direction was co-helmed by Nate Cash and Muto.<ref name=episodecredits>{{cite episode| title=Betty| series=Adventure Time| serieslink=|credits = Nate Cash, Adam Muto, & Nick Jennings (directors); Ako Castuera & Jesse Moynihan (writers) | network = [[Cartoon_Network|Cartoon Network]] |airdate=February 24, 2014 | season = 5 | number = 48}}</ref> An episode centered on Betty had been promised by the crew at [[San_Diego_Comic-Con_International|San Diego Comic-Con International]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Graham|first=Bill|title=Comic-Con: Adventure Time Panel Features Live Radio Play With Audio; A Brief Look At New Flame Princess Episode|url=http://collider.com/comic-con-adventure-time-recap/|work=Collider|accessdate=February 23, 2014|date=2012}}</ref> Moynihan had originally submitted an idea to the outline writers, who in turn worked with him and rewrote it to produce the final episode.<ref>{{cite web|last=Moynihan|first=Jesse|title=[Concerning the origin of 'Betty' and 'Breezy']|url=http://jmoyns.tumblr.com/post/86063684141/hey-jesse-you-said-betty-was-an-idea-you-came-up-with|publisher=[[Tumblr|Tumblr]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521074813/http://jmoyns.tumblr.com/|archivedate=May 21, 2014|accessdate=May 20, 2014|date=May 17, 2014}}</ref> Moynihan later noted that his personal intention for the episode was to "convey the idea that for Simon, death was preferable to life as Ice King, but that love and sacrifice to another person could provide hope for a future."<ref name=jessebetty/> Huntress Wizard, a character popular with the ''Adventure Time'' fanbase, was originally supposed to be featured in the episode.<ref name=jessebetty/> Because "Betty" was already "jam packed", everything "non-essential" had to be cut out of the storyboard, which left Moynihan "heartbroken".<ref>{{cite web|last=Moynihan|first=Jesse|title=Jesse Moynihan – Post 613|url=http://landofooo.com/community/topic/3590-jesse-moynihan/?p=186285|publisher=LandOfOoo|accessdate=February 23, 2014|date=October 9, 2013}} Note: Information taken from [[Jesse_Moynihan|Jesse Moynihan]]'s [http://landofooo.com/community/topic/3590-jesse-moynihan/?p=160388 verified] account.</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Moynihan|first=Jesse|title=Huntress Wizard's Big Moment Gets Cut from the Board|url=http://instagram.com/p/Wk4QjvTcrk/|publisher=[[Instagram|Instagram]]|accessdate=February 23, 2014|date=February 2013}}</ref> He later used the "[[deleted_scene|deleted scene]]" for the episode's promotional artwork.<ref name=jessebetty>{{cite web|last=Moynihan|first=Jesse|title=Betty|url=http://jessemoynihan.com/?p=2161|publisher=JesseMoynihan.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305022930/http://jessemoynihan.com/?p=2161|archivedate=March 4, 2014|accessdate=February 23, 2014|date=February 22, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Moynihan|first=Jesse|title=Deleted Scene|url=http://instagram.com/p/kh7YqJTcjo/|publisher=[[Instagram|Instagram]]|accessdate=February 23, 2014|date=February 17, 2014}}</ref>

"Betty" stars comedienne and ''[[Girls_(TV_series)|Girls]]'' creator [[Lena_Dunham|Lena Dunham]] as Betty.<ref name=episodecredits/> Dunham and ''Adventure Time'' head writer [[Kent_Osborne|Kent Osborne]] were [[Facebook|Facebook]] friends, and knew each other from the [[independent_film|independent film]] scene. When the crew approached her, she was excited and interested because she had a [[Godparent|goddaughter]] who was a fan. She recorded her lines while she was in production for ''Girls'' in New York.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adventure Time (2014): Adam Muto & Kent Osborne Interview|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mYhjZHc9_ms|website=''[[YouTube|YouTube]]''|publisher=HappyCool|accessdate=August 4, 2014|date=July 25, 2014}}</ref> The episode also marks the return of several guest stars. [[Miguel_Ferrer|Miguel Ferrer]] reprises his role as Death, and [[Steve_Agee|Steve Agee]] returns as Ash.<ref name=twittermuto>{{cite web|last=Muto|first=Adam|title=[Guest stars from the episode]|url=https://twitter.com/MrMuto/status/438037194779791360|publisher=[[Twitter|Twitter]]|accessdate=February 25, 2014|date=February 24, 2014}}</ref> Ferrer had last appeared in the [[Adventure_Time_(season_4)|fourth season]] episode "[[Sons_of_Mars_(Adventure_Time)|Sons of Mars]]", whereas Agee had appeared in the [[Adventure_Time_(season_3)|third season]] episode "Memory of a Memory".<ref>{{cite episode| title=Sons of Mars| series=Adventure Time| serieslink=|credits = Larry Leichliter (director); Ako Castuera & Jesse Moynihan (writers) | network = [[Cartoon_Network|Cartoon Network]] |airdate=July 23, 2012| season = 4 | number = 15}}</ref><ref>{{cite episode| title=Memory of a Memory| series=Adventure Time| serieslink=|credits = Larry Leichliter (director); Ako Castuer & Tom Herpich (writers) | network = [[Cartoon_Network|Cartoon Network]] |airdate=July 25, 2011| season = 3 | number = 3}}</ref> Comedian [[Duncan_Trussell|Duncan Trussell]] reprises his role as Ron James; he had previous appeared in the fifth season episode "Wizards Only, Fools".<ref name=twittermuto/><ref name=wof>{{cite episode| title=Wizards Only, Fools| series=Adventure Time| serieslink=|credits = Nate Cash & Nick Jennings (directors); Jesse Moynihan & Thomas Wellmann (writers) | network = [[Cartoon_Network|Cartoon Network]] |airdate=July 1, 2013| season = 5 | number = 26}}</ref> [[Maurice_LaMarche|Maurice LaMarche]] reprises his recurring role voicing the Grand Master Wizard; he also voices Belle Noche in the series.<ref name=twittermuto/><ref>{{cite web|last=Muto|first=Adam|title=What is the correct, Bellonocci, Bellanocci, Bollonoche or Bellanoche?|url=http://new.spring.me/#!/maslovarodrigu/q/562482684757037950|publisher=[[Formspring|Formspring]]|accessdate=February 25, 2014|date=February 2014}}</ref>

==Reception==
"Betty" aired on February 24, 2014 on [[Cartoon_Network|Cartoon Network]].<ref name=episodecredits/> The episode was watched by 1.713 million viewers, and received a [[Nielsen_rating|Nielsen household rating]] rating of 1.2.<ref name=rating/> Nielsen ratings are [[audience_measurement|audience measurement]] systems that determine the audience size and composition of [[broadcast_programming|television programming]] in the United States, which means that the episode was seen by 1.2 percent of all households at the time of the broadcast. The episode was the 4th most-watched episode aired by Cartoon Network for the week of February 24 to March 2, 2014.<ref name=rating>{{cite web|last=Pucci|first=Douglas|title=Cartoon Network Ratings (February 24-March 2, 2014)|url=http://sonofthebronx.blogspot.com/2014/03/cartoon-network-ratings-february-24.html|work=[[Son_of_the_Bronx|Son of the Bronx]]|publisher=[[Blogger_(service)|Blogger]]|accessdate=March 8, 2014|date=March 8, 2014}}</ref>


Oliver Sava of ''[[The_A.V._Club|The A.V. Club]]'' awarded it an "A" and called it a "huge episode for the Ice King", because it marked "a major shift in the character's future by reconnecting with his past lover", Betty.<ref name=avclub/> Sava noted that it was designed to "jump-start the momentum by introducing new characters and storylines for future episodes", and that its premise opens up various storytelling avenues for the future of the series.<ref name=avclub/> He also applauded the casting of Dunham as Betty, noting that she "finds the emotional truth underneath the absurd situation to balance the drama and comedy of the script."<ref name=avclub>{{cite web|last=Sava|first=Oliver|title=Adventure Time: 'Betty'|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/adventure-time-betty-201462|work=[[The_A.V._Club|The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The_Onion|The Onion]]|accessdate=February 25, 2014|date=February 24, 2014}}</ref> Nexi Pandell of [[Wired_(magazine)|''Wired'' magazine]] named the episode one of "Episodes You Can’t Skip".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pandell|first1=Nexi|title=Wired Binge-Watching Guide: Adventure Time|url=http://www.wired.com/2015/04/binge-guide-adventure-time/|website=[[Wired_(magazine)|Wired]]|publisher=[[Condé_Nast|Condé Nast]]|accessdate=April 11, 2015|date=April 8, 2015}}</ref>-->

